gh often this type of rare accidental is expressed as a natural, followed by a flat () to make this clear. Likewise (and more commonly), a double sharp sign on a key signature with a single sharp indicates only a double sharp, not a triple sharp.", "qas": [{"question": "where are accidentals placed before symbols ?", "answers": [], "id": "(2, 7, 0)"}]}, {"context": "Assuming enharmonicity, many accidentals will create equivalences between pitches that are written differently. For instance, raising the note B to B is equal to the note C. Assuming all such equivalences, the complete chromatic scale adds five additional pitch classes to the original seven lettered notes for a total of 12 (the 13th note completing the octave), each separated by a half-step.", "qas": [{"question": "how many extra pitch classes are there ?", "answers": [], "id": "(2, 8, 1)"}]}, {"context": "Notes that belong to the diatonic scale relevant in the context are sometimes called \"diatonic notes\"; notes that do not meet that criterion are then sometimes called \"chromatic notes\".", "qas": [{"question": "what are the notes that do not meet the diatonic scale ?", "answers": [], "id": "(2, 9, 0)"}]}, {"context": "Another style of notation, rarely used in English, uses the suffix \"is\" to indicate a sharp and \"es\" (only \"s\" after A and E) for a flat, e.g., Fis for F, Ges for G, Es for E. This system first arose in Germany and is used in almost all European countries whose main language is not English, Greek, or a Romance language.", "qas": []}, {"context": "In most countries using these suffixes, the letter H is used to represent what is B natural in English, the letter B is used instead of B, and Heses (i.e., H) is used instead of B (although Bes and Heses both denote the English B). Dutch-speakers in Belgium and the Netherlands use the same suffixes, but applied throughout to the notes A to G, so that B, B and B have the same meaning as in English, although they are called B, Bes, and Bes