 the nose along with an obstruction in the mouth, means that nasal occlusives behave both like sonorants and like obstruents. For example, nasals tend to pattern with other sonorants such as and , but in many languages, they may develop from or into stops.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Acoustically, nasals have bands of energy at around 200 and 2,000\u00a0Hz.\n1. The symbol is commonly used to represent the dental nasal as well, rather than , as it is rarely distinguished from the alveolar nasal.", "qas": []}, {"context": "Examples of languages containing nasal occlusives:", "qas": []}, {"context": "The voiced retroflex nasal is is a common sound in Languages of India.", "qas": []}, {"context": "The voiced palatal nasal is a common sound in European languages, such as: Spanish , French and Italian , Catalan and Hungarian , Czech and Slovak , Polish , Occitan and Portuguese , and (before a vowel) Modern Greek .", "qas": []}, {"context": "Many Germanic languages, including German, Dutch, English and Swedish, as well as varieties of Chinese such as Mandarin and Cantonese, have , and . Tamil has a six-fold distinction between , , , , and (\u0bae,\u0ba8,\u0ba9,\u0ba3,\u0b9e,\u0b99).", "qas": []}, {"context": "Catalan, Occitan, Spanish, and Italian have , , as phonemes, and and as allophones. Nevertheless, in several American dialects of Spanish, there is no palatal nasal but only a palatalized nasal, , as in English \"canyon\".", "qas": []}, {"context": "In Brazilian Portuguese and Angolan Portuguese , written , is typically pronounced as , a nasal palatal approximant, a nasal glide (in Polish, this feature is also possible as an allophone). Semivowels in Portuguese often nasalize before and always after nasal vowels, resulting in and . What would be coda nasal occlusives in other West Iberian languages is only slightly pronounced before dental consonants. Outside this environment the nasality is spread over the vowel or become a nasal diphthong (\"mambembe\" , outside the 